# Code owners
#
# An owner listed here has review authority over the matching paths; GitHub requests their
# review automatically on any pull request that touches one.
#
# HONEST NOTE ON THIS FILE
# -----------------------
# Melkor has one maintainer. Every rule below therefore resolves to the same person, and this
# file does not describe a division of labour — it describes a bottleneck. That is deliberate.
# A CODEOWNERS file populated with invented handles or placeholder teams would imply a review
# capacity the project does not have, and would also fail silently: GitHub ignores an owner it
# cannot resolve or who lacks write access, so a path "owned" by a fictional reviewer is a path
# with no owner at all. The bus-factor consequences are stated in GOVERNANCE.md.
#
# The path-specific rules exist even though they are currently redundant, because they record
# *why* each area is sensitive. When reviewers or a second maintainer are added, ownership of
# these paths must stay narrow rather than widening by default.
#
# Ordering: the last matching rule wins, so the catch-all comes first and the sensitive paths
# come last.

# Default owner. Every change needs maintainer review today.
*                                   @sepahead

# --- Build and dependency surface ---------------------------------------------------------
# The build system decides what is compiled into a distributed artifact and with which
# hardening flags; a change here can quietly disable a sanitizer or a warning gate.
/CMakeLists.txt                     @sepahead
/cmake/                             @sepahead
/pyproject.toml                     @sepahead
/VERSION                            @sepahead

# --- Vendored third-party code and licence evidence ---------------------------------------
# Changes here move the redistributable boundary and alter the licence obligations of every
# downstream consumer. A permissively licensed core must not acquire copyleft or research-only
# source without an explicit, reviewed decision.
/third_party/                       @sepahead
/THIRD_PARTY_LICENSES.md            @sepahead
/NOTICE                             @sepahead
/LICENSE                            @sepahead
/tools/verify_third_party.py        @sepahead
/tools/generate_notices.py          @sepahead

# --- Untrusted-input parsers and resource limits -------------------------------------------
# The primary attack surface. Everything reachable from a crafted GLB, PLY, or SPZ file is a
# security boundary, and a defect there is a vulnerability rather than an ordinary crash.
/src/io/                            @sepahead
/include/melkor/io/                 @sepahead
/src/glb_reader.cpp                 @sepahead
/src/spz_encoder.cpp                @sepahead
/src/ply_writer.cpp                 @sepahead
/include/melkor/limits.hpp          @sepahead
/include/melkor/budget.hpp          @sepahead
/include/melkor/checked.hpp         @sepahead

# --- Release tooling and evidence -----------------------------------------------------------
# Produces the artifacts and the provenance a consumer uses to decide whether to trust a
# download. A change here can make a release claim more than it can prove.
/scripts/build_release_evidence.py  @sepahead
/release/                           @sepahead
/tools/build_source_bundle.py       @sepahead
/tools/check_version_sync.py        @sepahead
/docs/RELEASE.md                    @sepahead

# --- Pipeline and external-adapter scripts --------------------------------------------------
# These scripts pass user-supplied paths to shells and fetch external tools; command injection
# and unverified downloads are in scope for the security policy.
/scripts/                           @sepahead
/docs/adapters/                     @sepahead

# --- Desktop packaging ----------------------------------------------------------------------
# The Tauri surface decides what the shipped desktop application is permitted to touch.
/viewer/src-tauri/                  @sepahead

# --- CI, automation, and supply chain -------------------------------------------------------
# Workflows execute with repository credentials. A change here can exfiltrate a secret or
# publish a forged artifact, which makes it the most sensitive path in the repository.
/.github/workflows/                 @sepahead
/.github/dependabot.yml             @sepahead

# --- Security and governance ----------------------------------------------------------------
# Self-amendment must never be silent: the documents that define the threat model, the review
# rules, and who may approve a release are owned by the maintainer.
/SECURITY.md                        @sepahead
/GOVERNANCE.md                      @sepahead
/MAINTAINERS.md                     @sepahead
/CODE_OF_CONDUCT.md                 @sepahead
/SUPPORT.md                         @sepahead
/.github/CODEOWNERS                 @sepahead
